Brick 8a of the self-hosting arc: teach the tokenizer to TRAVERSE MULTIPLE LINES
and emit a line-boundary token, WITHOUT yet computing indentation. This is the
first half of the INDENT/DEDENT work (brick 8b adds the column stack and the
INDENT/DEDENT tokens next).

The problem: the pre-8a flat tokenizer STOPPED at the first newline. `skip_spaces`
advances over inline spaces (byte 32) only, not a newline (byte 10); the newline
fell through to the operator classifier, which returned 0, so the scanner read it
as end-of-input and the token list ended at the first line break. A multi-line
source could not even be traversed.

Brick 8a adds a line-boundary token kind (Newline, carrying the byte offset of
the newline). The next-lexeme recognizer, after skipping inline spaces, now
recognizes byte 10 as a Newline token; the token-end helper advances exactly one
byte past it; and the whole-source scanner conses the Newline like any other
token and keeps scanning the next line. Brick 8a emits newlines FAITHFULLY:
consecutive newlines (blank lines) emit consecutive Newline tokens — collapsing
blanks and the column-stack INDENT/DEDENT logic are brick 8b. Brick 8a computes
NO indentation, columns, INDENT, or DEDENT.

The trailing-end convention is unchanged from brick 2: the scanner always
appends one end-of-input cell, so a source with N real lexemes and K newlines
produces N + K + 1 token cells.

Validation is STRUCTURAL (multi-line evaluation is not meaningful yet): a
cell-counting driver tokenizes a source and counts every token cons cell, and a
kind-at-index driver tokenizes a source and returns the kind code of the token at
a given index (confirming the Newline appears at the right position). Both are
hand-derivable single numbers. Newline-bearing sources are checked NATIVE-ONLY
via argv (a real byte-10 newline), because the interpreter's JSON input reader
does not decode an escaped newline into a real newline byte — it passes the two
bytes backslash-n verbatim — exactly the same limit that made brick 5's comma
cases and brick 7's string cases native-only. Single-line cell counts cross-check
native against the interpreter through the JSON fixture. Bricks 1-7 are unchanged
on single-line input (a line with no newline byte takes the identical scan path),
which the unchanged eval and shape drivers certify.

  next lexeme = (skip inline spaces) then
                  Newline      if at a newline byte    -- brick 8a
                | Keyword | Ident | Number | String | Operator | Eof

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Brick 7 of the self-hosting arc: extend the parser's `primary` with two LITERAL
kinds — boolean literals (`true` / `false`) and string literals (`"..."`).
Brick 6 added the conditional expression; brick 7 adds the remaining leaf forms.

Boolean literals lex as keywords (the keyword classifier gains `true` = code 9
in the four-letter band and `false` = code 10 in a new five-letter band), parse
to a boolean-literal node carrying 1 for true / 0 for false, and DO carry an
arithmetic value — they evaluate to 1/0 and compose in and / or / not /
comparisons exactly as a 1/0 number would (true and false = 0, true or false = 1,
not false = 1, if true then 7 else 8 = 7).

String literals are the tokenizer-reopening part. A new string-length scanner
recognizes a `"`...`"` token with the closed escape set (\n \r \t \\ \"). Inside
the string a backslash starts a TWO-byte escape and is skipped unconditionally,
so an escaped quote (\") does NOT terminate the string; the string ends at the
first UNESCAPED closing quote. Escape handling is LENIENT — this is a token-
BOUNDARY scanner, not an escape validator, so an unknown escape \x is simply two
literal bytes (the reference lexer rejects unknown escapes, but finding where the
token ends is all this brick needs). An UNTERMINATED string (no closing quote
before end-of-source) runs to the end and is still a string token (fail-closed:
every byte index is guarded, and a trailing lone backslash counts as one byte and
stops). The string token carries its source span (opening-quote offset + total
length including both quotes), and the parser builds a string-literal node
identified by that span. A string has no arithmetic value without an environment
to decode its bytes, so it evaluates to zero — its correctness is proven
STRUCTURALLY by the shape signature (a dedicated top band per literal kind:
booleans and strings each get their own weight above the conditional's band).
Because the interpreter's JSON input reader cannot deliver a `"`-containing
source string (it strips outer quotes naively and does not decode escapes), the
string-literal cases are validated NATIVE-ONLY via argv, exactly like brick 5's
comma cases. The boolean and the non-string shape cases cross-check native
against the interpreter through the JSON fixture as before.

  primary = 'if' parse_or 'then' parse_or 'else' parse_or   -- brick 6
          | 'true' | 'false'    -- brick 7 boolean literal
          | STRING               -- brick 7 string literal
          | '(' parse_or ')' | NUMBER | IDENT trailer

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Brick 6 of the self-hosting arc: extend the parser's `primary` with a
conditional expression — `if cond then thn else els`, the single-line form.
Bricks 3-5 built the full-precedence parser (arithmetic core, logical or/and,
comparisons, prefix unary, then identifiers / calls / field access). Brick 6
adds the highest-level alternative to a primary: an `if` keyword opens a
conditional whose condition, then-branch, and else-branch are each a full
expression (parse_or). There is NO INDENT/DEDENT in this tokenizer, so only the
single-line form exists — the multi-line `if`/`then`/`else` block is a later
brick once a column-stack tokenizer ships.

  primary = 'if' parse_or 'then' parse_or 'else' parse_or   -- brick 6
          | '(' parse_or ')' | NUMBER | IDENT trailer
  trailer = '(' arglist ')'    -- function call
          | ('.' IDENT)*       -- field-access chain (left-deep)
          | (nothing)          -- a bare variable reference
  arglist = (parse_or (',' parse_or)*)?   -- zero or more comma-separated exprs

The else-branch is a full parse_or, so `if 1 then 2 else 3 + 100` parses the
else as `3 + 100` (= 103) and evaluates to 2 (the then-branch, since cond is
true) — the conditional does NOT stop the else at `3`. An if-expression is the
highest-precedence form, so it nests inside arithmetic only via parentheses:
`1 + (if 1 then 2 else 3)` = 3; a bare `1 + if ...` would parse the `if` as the
right operand of `+` (since parse_primary handles `if`), which is consistent but
the parenthesized form is the readable one tested here.

The tokenizer gains a four-letter-keyword classifier (`then` = code 7, `else` =
code 8) wired alongside the existing two- and three-letter ones (if / or / of /
let / and / not). The keyword `if` already lexes as code 1.

After lexing an identifier the parser peeks the next token: a '(' opens a
comma-separated argument list (a call), a '.' opens a field-access chain, and
anything else leaves a bare variable. Calls and fields nest: f(g(x)) and a.b.c
both parse, the latter left-deep. The argument list is itself a recursive
cons-list builder over the token stream, exactly like the tokenizer building the
token list.

Validation is STRUCTURAL, not numeric: a variable / call / field node has no
value without an environment, so brick 5's `shape` driver tokenizes + parses and
returns a kind-count fingerprint of the AST (10000*calls + 1000*fields +
100*vars + 10*bins + unaries) whose value is hand-derivable and distinct per
test input. The brick-3/4 evaluator (`eval_expr`) is unchanged and still
computes variable-free expressions (2+3*4 = 14); the new nodes evaluate to 0
there (out of the arithmetic evaluator's scope).

1. Declare a concept group holding the token types from brick 2 (a classified
   Token and a cons-list TokenList), an expression AST (a numeric leaf, a
   binary-operator node, a unary-not node, a unary-negation node, a bare-
   variable node carrying a source span, a field-access node, a function-call
   node carrying a callee span and an argument cons-list, and an error leaf), an
   argument cons-list, a parse result pairing an AST node with the token index
   where parsing ended, and a call-argument parse result pairing an argument
   cons-list with its end index.

2. A scanner state holds the source text and a byte position.

3. Skip spaces: advance the position past ASCII spaces.

4. Count the run of decimal digits starting at the position.

5. Compute ten to the power n for small n (digit-position weight).

6. Decode the decimal value of the digit run at the position.

7. Recognize identifiers and the logical keywords (and / or / not), classify the
   operator or punctuation at the position (two-char operators before one-char
   ones), and report an operator's byte length.

8. The byte length of an operator (two for two-char operators, one otherwise).

9. Recognize the next core lexeme at the position: an identifier or keyword, a
   number, an operator, or end of input.

10. The byte offset just past the next token.

11. Scan the whole source into a cons-list of tokens with a trailing end-of-input
    sentinel.

12. Drop the first n cons cells of a token list (a list plus an index).

13. Token accessors: the head token of a list, the kind code of a token, and the
    literal value carried by a number token.

14. Peek the kind code and the literal value of the token at a given index.

15. The parser carries the whole token list plus the current index. A fold state
    additionally carries the left-associative accumulator AST; a unary-wrap state
    carries the parsed operand and which prefix it was. Two accessors pull the
    node and the next-index out of a parse result. (Language note: a block-form
    match cannot currently be the right-hand side of a let binding — it is only
    legal in the final assignment position — so destructuring a parse result is
    factored into these two tiny rules.)

16. Parse a primary: a parenthesized expression (which reopens the grammar at the
    top, so a full or/and/comparison expression may appear in parentheses), or a
    number literal, or an identifier — which is a function call when followed by a
    parenthesized argument list, a field-access chain when followed by one or more
    dotted field names, or otherwise a bare variable reference identified by its
    source span; or an error leaf. Parse a (possibly empty) comma-separated
    argument list as a cons-list, consuming the closing parenthesis; fold a chain
    of dotted field accesses onto a base, left-deep. A primary is the highest-
    precedence form.

17. Fold multiplication, division, and modulo onto an accumulator, left-
    associatively, by parsing the next unary operand and recursing.

18. Parse a prefix-unary expression: a 'not' keyword or a leading '-' wraps the
    rest in the corresponding unary node (right-recursive); otherwise it is a
    primary. Then parse a multiplicative expression: a unary operand followed by
    any number of times, divide, or modulo operations.

19. Fold addition and subtraction onto an accumulator, left-associatively. Then
    parse a comparison: an additive expression optionally followed by ONE
    comparison operator (equal, not-equal, less, greater, less-equal,
    greater-equal) and another additive expression. Comparison is non-associative
    and binds looser than the arithmetic operators.

20. Fold the 'and' keyword onto an accumulator, left-associatively, by parsing the
    next comparison and recursing. Parse an 'and' expression: a comparison
    followed by any number of 'and's. 'and' binds looser than comparisons.

21. Fold the 'or' keyword onto an accumulator, left-associatively, by parsing the
    next 'and' expression and recursing. Parse the full expression: an 'and'
    expression followed by any number of 'or's. 'or' binds looser than 'and'.

22. Evaluate an expression AST to a number, recursing on the tree and dispatching
    each binary node on its operator (arithmetic to its value, comparisons and
    logical and/or to one or zero), negating or logically-negating each unary
    node.

23. Compute a STRUCTURAL signature of an AST: a kind-count fingerprint summing a
    large weight per function call, a smaller weight per field access, a smaller
    one per variable, a smaller one per binary node, and one per unary node, while
    recursing into a call's arguments. End to end (the structural driver):
    tokenize the source, parse the full expression from the start, and return the
    signature — proving that a call with two arguments builds a call node over a
    two-element argument list and that a.b.c builds nested field accesses, by a
    number predictable by hand.

24. End to end (the numeric driver, unchanged from brick 4): tokenize the source,
    parse the full expression from the start, and evaluate the resulting AST. This
    proves precedence ordering across all levels: one plus two equals three is one
    (addition binds tighter than the comparison), and two less-than three and four
    less-than five is one (the comparisons bind tighter than 'and'). Variable,
    call, and field nodes have no value without an environment and evaluate to
    zero here — their correctness is proven by the structural signature above. A
    conditional expression evaluates its condition, then ONLY the selected branch
    (the language's lazy if): if two less-than three then ten else twenty is ten.

25. The conditional expression (brick 6). The parser carries the partial state of
    an if-expression through a small chain of single-input continuation rules,
    because a rule has one input and let bindings are eager: a state holding the
    token list and the parsed condition (then-state), one holding the token list,
    the condition node, and the parsed then-branch (else-state), and one holding
    the condition and then nodes and the parsed else-branch (build-state). The
    then-state continuation consumes the 'then' keyword and parses the then-branch;
    the else-state continuation consumes the 'else' keyword and parses the
    else-branch; the build-state continuation assembles the conditional node from
    the three sub-expressions, carrying the else-branch's end index. The keyword
    classifier additionally recognizes the four-letter keywords 'then' and 'else'.
    Evaluation walks a conditional by evaluating its condition and then only the
    selected branch.

26. Line traversal and the line-boundary token (brick 8a). A line-boundary token
    kind carries the byte offset of a newline. The next-lexeme recognizer, after
    skipping inline spaces, recognizes a newline byte as that token; the token-end
    helper advances exactly one byte past it; the whole-source scanner conses it
    like any other token and continues onto the next line, lifting the old "stops
    at the first newline" limit. A structural test reports whether a token is a
    line-boundary token. A cell-counting driver tokenizes a source and counts
    every token cons cell (lexeme cells plus line-boundary cells plus the trailing
    end-of-input cell). A kind-at-index driver tokenizes a source and returns the
    kind code of the token at a given index, confirming the line-boundary token
    lands at the right position. No indentation, columns, or block-structure
    tokens are computed — that is brick 8b's column stack.

27. Indentation and block-structure tokens (brick 8b). A column stack records the
    indentation width of every open block (a cons-list of widths, with a column-0
    sentinel that is never popped). A line driver processes the source line by
    line, threading the stack: it measures each line's leading-space width,
    compares it to the stack's top, and weaves block tokens into the stream — one
    indent token (and a push) when the line is deeper, one dedent token per closed
    level (and the matching pops) when it is shallower, and nothing when it is the
    same. Tabs in the indentation and a width that matches no enclosing block both
    produce a distinguished error token (a Verbose rule is total, so an error is a
    token, not an abort). Blank lines are skipped. At end of input a dedent token
    is flushed for every still-open level, then the trailing end-of-input token.
    A structural-signature driver tokenizes a source with indentation and returns
    a kind-count fingerprint (a dedicated band per block-token kind) so each test
    input's block structure is a single hand-derivable number; newline-bearing
    sources are native-only (the interpreter's data reader does not decode an
    escaped newline into a real newline byte).

28. Parse a statement BLOCK (brick 9): the first PROGRAM-grammar parse that
    consumes the block-structure tokens. A block body is a sequence of zero or
    more let-statements followed by a final out-statement:

        let_stmt = 'let' IDENT '=' expr
        out_stmt = IDENT '=' expr            (conventionally `out = expr`)

    where each expr is a full precedence-aware expression (the brick 1-8 parser).
    A binding is a cons-list cell carrying the bound name as a source span plus its
    right-hand-side expression subtree; a block is the binding list plus the final
    out-expression. The block parser skips any leading separators (line-boundary
    and indent tokens), then dispatches on the leading token: the `let` keyword
    starts a let-statement (the name is the following identifier, the value a full
    expression after `=`), and a continuation threads the value's end index into
    the recursive parse of the rest of the block, consing the binding; a bare
    identifier followed by `=` is the final out-statement, ending the block with
    the accumulated bindings and the out-expression. The recursion into the rest
    of the block sits inside the let-branch's continuation (never an eager
    binding), so it fires only along the taken path.

    BLOCK FRAMING (documented): the brick-9 test sources are the block BODY lines
    written at column 0, so the token stream is lexemes-and-line-boundaries with no
    indent/dedent; the block parser is nonetheless framing-agnostic (it skips a
    leading indent and each statement's trailing line-boundary, and stops the
    binding sweep at a dedent or end-of-input), so a genuinely-indented block would
    parse identically. Validation is STRUCTURAL: a signature driver parses a block
    and returns `1000000 * (#bindings) + sum-of-binding-RHS-shapes +
    result-shape`, a single hand-derivable number per input certifying the exact
    (binding count, per-binding RHS shape, result shape) triple. Newline-bearing
    sources are native-only (escaped-newline decoding, as in brick 8a/8b).

    EVAL-WITH-ENVIRONMENT IS A FOLLOW-UP (not in this brick). A logic block whose
    bindings and result are arithmetic over the bound names is semantically
    evaluable: an environment maps each name to its value, the bindings fold in
    left-to-right, and the result evaluates with name lookup. Name resolution must
    compare name BYTES (two occurrences of the same name sit at different source
    spans), which requires threading the source text into a recursive evaluator
    over the AST. That recursive evaluator carries a text field in its input record
    and makes two sibling recursive calls within one arithmetic node; the current
    native backend clobbers the caller's text-field slots across the first of the
    two sibling calls, so the second sub-evaluation reads a corrupted source
    pointer and the binary fails closed. Until that native-backend gap is fixed,
    block semantics are proven structurally (the signature above), and
    eval-with-environment is deferred.

30. Parse a top-level RULE declaration with a logic block. This lifts the parser
    from a bare statement-block (item 28/29) to a real program ITEM: a named rule
    whose body is a logic block. The grammar, mirroring the reference compiler's
    rule parser restricted to a tractable subset, is

        rule_decl = 'rule' NAME newline indent
                      'logic' ':' newline indent
                        <statement-sequence>     -- the let-bindings + out value
                      dedent dedent

    Only the `rule` keyword, the rule NAME, and the `logic:` section are parsed;
    intention / source / input / output / proofs are later bricks. The words
    `rule` and `logic` have NO keyword code (the tokenizer classifies only
    if/or/of/let/and/not/then/else/true/false), so they lex as ordinary
    identifiers and are RECOGNIZED by byte-comparing each identifier's source span
    against the literal bytes "rule" / "logic". Because that comparison reads the
    actual source bytes, the rule-parsing entry carries the source text ALONGSIDE
    the token list (a record with both the token list and the source). The two
    nested block openings (entering the rule body, then the logic body) are
    consumed by skipping separator tokens (line-boundary AND indent): after the
    name the parser skips to the `logic` identifier, after the `:` it skips to the
    first statement; the two closing dedents need no explicit consumption because
    the block parser (item 28) already stops its sweep at a dedent or end-of-input.
    A Verbose rule is total, so a malformed header cannot abort: when both byte
    checks pass the body is the parsed block, otherwise the body is an empty block
    (a distinguishable signal, not a crash).

    A parsed rule declaration carries its name span plus its logic block, so it is
    BOTH evaluable and structurally checkable. The eval driver parses the rule
    decl, extracts its body block, folds the bindings into an environment, and
    evaluates the result — proving the header parsed AND the body still evaluates
    (the rule's `out` value). The structural driver returns
    `1000 * name_len + block_shape(body)`, a single hand-derivable number
    certifying the name length AND the body's full structural signature. Both are
    NATIVE-ONLY (the source is multi-line — escaped-newline decoding, as in items
    26/27/29; multi-line argv supplies the real newline bytes). Cross-check with
    the interpreter uses a JSON fixture whose string contains LITERAL newline
    bytes (the gap is only about backslash-n ESCAPES, which neither argv nor
    literal-byte JSON involve), and native equals interpreter for every input.

31. Parse a whole PROGRAM = a SEQUENCE of top-level rule declarations. This lifts
    the parser from ONE rule declaration (item 30) to a list of them, mirroring
    the reference compiler's top-level item loop (parse a rule, push it, repeat
    until end-of-input). The grammar is

        program = rule_decl*

    where each rule_decl is exactly item 30's shape. Consecutive declarations are
    separated, in the token stream, by the line-boundary plus the one-or-more
    DEDENT tokens that close the previous rule's logic body and rule body, after
    which the next `rule` identifier appears at column 0. To walk a sequence the
    parser must know where each declaration ENDS: the rule-decl parser is given a
    position-returning form that takes a start index and returns both the parsed
    declaration AND the token index just past its body (the body block's end
    index, item 28's threaded `next`). The program loop then, from that end index,
    skips ALL separator tokens — line-boundary, indent, AND dedent — to reach the
    next significant token; item 28's separator-skipper stops at a dedent (inside
    a block the dedent is the terminator), so the program level adds a wider
    skipper that also crosses dedents (between two sibling rules the closing
    dedents are mere noise). If that token's source span spells `rule` the loop
    parses one declaration there and conses it onto the recursively-parsed rest
    starting from its end index; otherwise (end-of-input or any non-`rule` token)
    the program ends with the empty list. Each consing step advances the cursor by
    at least a whole rule body, so the scan strictly approaches the finite end of
    the token list.

    A parsed program is a cons-list of rule declarations, the same shape as the
    token list / binding list / environment, so the same structural-recursion
    proof applies to its length. Two drivers validate it. The count driver returns
    the list length, proving the program split into the right number of
    declarations. The eval-nth driver takes the source plus an index n, drops the
    first n declarations to land on the n-th, takes its body block, folds its
    bindings into an environment, and evaluates the result — proving each
    declaration parsed AND its body is intact and evaluable (the n-th rule's `out`
    value). Both are NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source, as in item 30): the count
    driver takes the source as its single argument, the eval-nth driver takes the
    source plus n as two arguments. The money shot: a two-rule program whose
    bodies compute 5 and 8 parses to a length-2 program list whose first and
    second declarations evaluate to exactly 5 and 8.

32. A LINTER written in Verbose = a static check that consumes a parsed program
    (item 31) and reports a diagnostic count. This turns the parser front end
    into a TOOL: the headline driver returns the total number of undefined-
    variable references across every rule in the program (0 = clean). It does
    not evaluate anything — it analyzes the parsed AST shape.

    THE LINT: undefined variable references. For each rule, every variable
    referenced in its body — the `out =` result expression AND every let-
    binding's right-hand side — must be bound by a `let` in that same rule. A
    reference is an AST variable node (a name span); it is DEFINED iff that span
    is byte-equal to SOME binding name in the rule's binding list. A variable
    that matches no binding name is a lint error, counted once per occurrence.

    SCOPING RULE (whole-rule — the brick-13 baseline, refined in item 33). The
    first version treats a variable as defined iff it appears as ANY binding name
    in the rule's binding list — all of a rule's lets mutually in scope. So
    `let x = 1 / out = x + y` reports one error (y), and `let x = 1 / let y = x +
    1 / out = y` reports zero (x is in scope for y's RHS). This deliberately
    ignores let-order: a sound over-approximation of "defined somewhere in the
    rule" that never raises a false positive on a genuine binding, but does NOT
    catch use-before-definition within a let RHS. Item 33 refines exactly this:
    a let RHS sees only EARLIER lets.

    WHAT IS A VARIABLE (and what is not). Only an AST variable node counts. A
    call's callee name is a RULE name, not a variable — ignored; only the call's
    ARGUMENT expressions are walked. A field-access field name (the `.b` in a.b)
    is a record field name, not a variable — ignored; only the field-access BASE
    (`a`) is walked. Numbers, strings, booleans, and error nodes carry no
    reference.

    PER-RULE SCOPE. Each rule contributes only its own undefined references,
    because the check reads only that rule's own binding list — one rule's lets
    are never visible to another rule. A two-rule program where the first rule
    uses its own `let` and the second references an unbound name reports exactly
    one error (the second rule's), proving rule scopes do not leak.

    The membership probe walks the binding list comparing each binding name's
    span (length guard, then byte compare) against the queried name. The AST
    walker mirrors the structural-signature walker (item 23) but contributes
    each variable's undefined count instead of a shape band, descending into
    both children of a binary node, the single child of a negation/logical-not,
    all three sub-expressions of a conditional, the argument list of a call, and
    the base of a field access. The binding walker checks every let RHS against
    the rule scope; the rule check sums RHS errors plus result errors; the
    program fold sums over the rule list. Because every recursive lint rule
    packs its cons-list as a FIELD of its input (so it can carry the scope and
    source text alongside), it recurses over a field rather than over the input
    itself, so it uses the bound + recursion breadcrumb form (item 29's
    env-walker shape), not the structural FIELD proof (item 31's length form,
    which needs the input to BE the cons-list).

    NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line program source, as in items 30/31): the headline
    driver takes a scan state (source + position) so the source is the first
    argument and the position is the second (always 0). The money shot: a two-
    rule program whose second rule references an undefined `w` lints to exactly
    1 (and the first rule, which uses its own `let x`, is clean) — a real static
    check written in Verbose, run as native machine code over a parsed Verbose
    program.

33. USE-BEFORE-DEF refinement of the linter (item 32). Sharpen the whole-rule
    scoping into proper let-ordering: a let binding's right-hand side may only
    reference bindings that appear EARLIER in the source order (and not itself),
    while the `out =` result expression still sees ALL of the rule's lets. So
    `let a = b + 1 / let b = 2 / out = a` now reports one error — a's RHS uses b
    before b is defined — where the whole-rule baseline (item 32) reported zero.
    A self-reference `let x = x + 1` reports one error: x is not yet in scope for
    its own RHS. A legitimate later reference `let x = 1 / let y = x + 1 / out =
    y` stays zero, because x is earlier than y. The result expression is
    unaffected: `let p = 1 / let q = 2 / out = p + q` stays zero (the result
    legitimately sees every binding).

    HOW THE SCOPE IS THREADED. Instead of checking every let RHS against the
    whole binding list, the binding walker threads a PREFIX — the set of bindings
    already seen earlier in the list. At each binding it checks the RHS against
    the prefix ONLY, then recurses on the tail with the prefix extended by THIS
    binding. Because membership is order-agnostic (the probe asks "is this name
    one of the earlier binding names", not "where"), the prefix is built by
    consing the current binding onto the front of the accumulated prefix — that
    front-consed list is exactly the set of earlier bindings. The walk seeds the
    prefix empty. A self-reference is caught for free: the current binding is
    consed onto the prefix only when descending into the tail, AFTER its own RHS
    has been checked against a prefix that does not yet contain it.

    The money shot: `let a = b + 1 / let b = 2 / out = a` lints to 1
    (use-before-def caught) while `let x = 1 / let y = x + 1 / out = y` stays 0
    (proper let-ordering) — order-sensitive scope analysis, written in Verbose,
    run as native machine code. NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source), same scan-state
    invocation as items 31/32.

34. UNDEFINED-CALLEE detection: the linter's first INTER-rule pass (brick 15).
    The variable lint (items 32/33) is INTRA-rule — a variable resolves against
    the current rule's own bindings, so each rule is linted in isolation. A
    function call is different: it names a RULE, and a rule may be defined ANYWHERE
    in the program. So resolving a callee needs the WHOLE program's rule list, not
    just one rule's bindings. The headline driver returns the total number of
    calls that name a rule which does not exist. 0 = every call in the program
    resolves to a real rule.

    THE LINT: undefined callee references. For each rule, every function call
    `name(args...)` anywhere in the body (every let RHS AND the result) must name
    a rule that EXISTS in the program. A call to a non-existent rule is one error.
    The call's arguments are themselves expressions that may contain more calls, so
    a nested call `g(h(1))` is checked at both the outer callee (g) and the inner
    callee (h) — that is how nested-call resolution falls out of the recursion.

    PROGRAM-WIDE, ORDER-AGNOSTIC SCOPE. Unlike the let-ordering of item 33, callee
    scope has no order: a rule may call ITSELF (self-reference of a callee is legal
    — it is existence, not termination, that is checked here), and any other rule
    regardless of where it appears (forward calls, mutual recursion). So there is
    no prefix trick — every rule resolves its callees against the FULL program rule
    list. The fold over the program threads two rule lists: an `iter` that advances
    (one rule checked per step) and an `all` that stays fixed (the whole program),
    so badcall checking always sees every rule.

    A SEPARATE PASS, PROVABLY INDEPENDENT. The callee lint is kept distinct from
    the var/use-before-def walk: it carries the program's rule list where the var
    walk carries the rule's bindings. This separation is observable: a call
    `g(y)` where `g` exists but `y` is an undefined variable lints to 0 under the
    callee pass (the callee resolves) and 1 under the variable pass (y is unbound).
    The mirror case `g(h(1))` (no undefined variables, but `h` is not a rule) lints
    to 1 under the callee pass and 0 under the variable pass. The two passes never
    see each other's concern.

    HOW IT WALKS. A membership probe asks "does some rule in the program have a
    name span byte-equal to this callee span?" (the rule-name analogue of the
    binding-membership probe). The AST walker descends every node, and at each
    function-call node it adds 1 when the callee is not a known rule, then recurses
    into the call's arguments (catching nested calls). Variable references, numbers,
    strings, booleans, and the error node contribute nothing — they carry no
    callee. The per-rule checker sums the bad-callee counts of every let RHS and the
    result, all resolved against the full program rule list.

    The money shot: `rule f / logic: / out = g(h(1)) / rule g / logic: / out = 2`
    lints to 1 — g exists, h does not, the nested callee resolved across the whole
    program — a cross-rule static check, written in Verbose, run as native machine
    code over a parsed Verbose program. A clean self-call (`out = f(1)` inside f)
    and a clean mutual call (`out = g(1)` with g defined) both stay 0. NATIVE-ONLY
    (multi-line source), same scan-state invocation as items 31/32/33. The two
    driver passes (item 32/33's variable lint and this callee lint) are intended to
    be summed by a future combined linter; for now each is its own headline driver.


34. Brick 16 of the self-hosting arc: RULE PARAMETERS. The toy grammar so far had
    rules of the shape `rule NAME` then `logic:` — a name and a body, no formal
    parameters. Real Verbose rules take parameters: `rule add(x, y)` declares two
    formals x and y that are in scope throughout the body. Brick 16 parses the
    optional parameter list and makes the parameter names a first-class part of the
    rule declaration AND of the linter's scope.

    THE GRAMMAR. After the rule NAME, the next token MAY be `(`. If so, a
    comma-separated list of bare identifiers follows, closed by `)`:
    `rule add(x, y)` -> params [x, y]; `rule f()` -> no params (empty parens);
    `rule f` (no parens) -> no params (the parameter list is optional). The list is
    parsed exactly like a call's argument list (the same `(` / `,` / `)` token
    dispatch) but it collects bare NAME spans (a cons-list of (start, len) pairs)
    instead of argument AST nodes. After the list (or the name when there are no
    parens) the parser continues to `logic:` from the index just past the `)`.

    PARAMETERS ARE NAMES. A parameter is its bytes in the source text — the same
    identity model as a let-binding name or a variable reference. The parser does
    not decode the name; it stores the span. The rule declaration grows one field:
    its parameter list, carried alongside the name span and the logic block. Adding
    that field touches every place the declaration is built or destructured (the
    two header parsers and the field accessors); the verifier enforces that the
    field is supplied everywhere, which keeps the change mechanical and complete.

    PARAMETERS ARE THE INITIAL SCOPE. This is the linter half of the brick. A
    parameter is a DEFINED variable everywhere in the body: a let RHS may reference
    it, and the result may reference it, with no `let` introducing it. The cleanest
    way to make the existing scope machinery honor this is to convert the parameter
    list into a binding list (each parameter becomes a binding whose NAME is the
    parameter span and whose value is a dummy — the membership check only ever
    reads the name, never the value) and use that list as the BASE scope. The
    use-before-def walk over the lets is then seeded with the parameters as its
    starting prefix (so a parameter is "already seen" before the first let), and
    the result is checked against the parameters appended to the full binding list.
    Because membership is order-agnostic, appending the two lists in any order is
    correct; the only requirement is that every name from both is present.

    EVALUATION is unchanged and orthogonal: there is no call mechanism yet, so a
    parameter has no value at evaluation time (like a free variable). A rule with
    parameters whose body uses only literals and lets still evaluates correctly;
    evaluating a body that references a parameter yields the unbound-variable value
    (0), exactly as a variable with no binding does. Brick 16 is a PARSE + LINT
    brick, not an eval brick — the eval drivers are verified to still produce the
    right number when the body does not depend on a parameter's value.

    THE MONEY SHOT: `rule add(x, y) / logic: / out = x + y` parses with 2
    parameters and lints to 0 (x and y are in scope as parameters), while the same
    rule with `out = x + z` lints to 1 (z is neither a parameter nor a let). A
    parse driver returns the parameter count of the first rule (2 for `add(x, y)`,
    0 for `f()` and for the no-paren form); the lint driver counts undefined
    references with parameters treated as the initial scope. Both are NATIVE-ONLY
    (multi-line source), same scan-state invocation as items 30-33. Rule parameters
    parsed and scoped, in pure Verbose, run as native machine code.


35. Brick 17 of the self-hosting arc: CALL-ARITY checking — the linter's SECOND
    inter-rule pass. The callee pass (item 34, brick 15) asks "does the called
    rule EXIST?". This pass asks the next question down: "does the call pass the
    RIGHT NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS?". A call `add(1)` to a rule `rule add(x, y)` is
    well-formed for the callee pass (add exists) but WRONG here — one argument
    supplied, two parameters declared. The headline driver returns the total
    number of call sites whose argument count does not match the called rule's
    parameter count. 0 = every call to an existing rule is well-arged.

    ONLY EXISTING RULES ARE CHECKED. An undefined callee is the callee pass's
    concern, not this one: if a call names a rule that does not exist, this pass
    contributes 0 for that call — you cannot compare against an arity that is not
    there. This makes the two passes PROVABLY INDEPENDENT and complementary:
    `g(1, 2)` with g undefined lints 1 under the callee pass and 0 here; `add(1)`
    with add a real 2-parameter rule lints 0 under the callee pass and 1 here.
    The arity pass needs the callee to exist before it has anything to say; the
    callee pass needs the callee to NOT exist before it has anything to say.

    PROGRAM-WIDE, ORDER-AGNOSTIC SCOPE — identical to the callee pass. A call may
    target a rule defined anywhere (forward, self, mutual), so the structure
    mirrors the callee pass exactly: a probe over the program's rule list that
    returns the matched rule's parameter count (instead of a 0/1 membership flag),
    an Ast/ArgList mutual walk, a per-rule split (every let RHS plus the result),
    and an iter/all fold over the program (iter advances one rule per step, all
    stays fixed so every rule resolves its calls against every rule).

    THE NOT-FOUND SENTINEL. The arity probe returns 1000000 (one million) when no
    rule of the queried name exists — deliberately NOT -1. A `number` field
    defaults to the range [0, i32::MAX], and the optimizer's interval arithmetic
    could dead-eliminate a branch that tests a negative value. 1000000 is safely
    inside the field range, far above any real parameter count, and the
    `found == 1000000` skip test is exact. Counting the arguments of a call and
    the parameters of a rule are the same structural-recursion shape over their
    respective cons-lists (the argument-count rule is the exact mirror of the
    parameter-count rule from brick 16). The per-call decision is factored into a
    tiny helper so the arity probe is evaluated exactly once per call (no inline
    double-evaluation): 0 if the callee is undefined or the counts match, 1 if the
    callee exists and the counts differ.

    THE MONEY SHOT: `rule add(x, y) / logic: / out = x + y` plus a caller doing
    `out = add(1, 2)` lints to 0 (2 args, 2 params), while the same caller doing
    `out = add(1)` lints to 1 (1 arg, 2 params). A call to an undefined `g(1, 2)`
    lints to 0 here (arity skips it — the callee pass counts it). A self-call with
    correct arity (`rule f(n) / out = f(n)`) stays 0; the same with a wrong arity
    (`out = f(n, n)`) lints to 1 — a rule mis-calling itself, caught across the
    whole program. NATIVE-ONLY (multi-line source), same scan-state invocation as
    items 30-34. A second cross-rule static check, written in Verbose, run as
    native machine code over a parsed Verbose program — independent of both the
    variable lint and the callee lint, intended to be summed by a future combined
    linter; for now each is its own headline driver.

36. Brick 18 of the self-hosting arc: CALL/APPLY in the evaluator — make the
    interpreter actually EXECUTE function calls. Through brick 17 the evaluator
    (item 22, brick 10) resolved VARIABLES against an environment but returned 0
    for every CALL. Brick 18 closes that gap: an AstCall now (1) finds the called
    rule by NAME in the program, (2) evaluates the argument expressions against
    the CALLER's environment, (3) binds them positionally to the callee's formal
    parameters in a FRESH environment (lexical scoping — the callee does NOT see
    the caller's locals), (4) folds the callee's own let-bindings on top of that,
    and (5) evaluates the callee's result expression. The whole front end is now a
    (toy) INTERPRETER: source text -> tokens -> AST -> a real computed call result.

    THE THREADING. The program's parsed rule list is threaded through the
    evaluator so a call can resolve its callee. The two evaluator inputs
    (eval_ast_env's and build_env's) each gain a `prog` field carrying the rule
    list, and every recursive construction of those inputs passes it down. A new
    eval_call probe carries the callee name span + the call's argument list + the
    caller env + the source + the program; a new bind_params probe walks the
    callee's parameter list and the call's argument list in lock-step, evaluating
    each argument in the caller env and consing (param name span, computed value)
    onto a fresh empty environment; a new find_rule probe walks the program's rule
    list and returns the RuleDecl whose name span byte-matches (the same name
    matching idiom as the arity / callee passes), with a SENTINEL empty rule whose
    body is AstErr on no match — so a call to a nonexistent rule evaluates to 0,
    preserving the pre-brick-18 "AstCall => 0" behavior (the undefined-callee lint
    flags it separately). Two tiny arg_head / arg_tail probes read the head and
    tail of an argument list (block-form match is only legal in final position, so
    destructuring an ArgList is factored out — the same idiom as the parsed_args
    accessors). A call with fewer args than params binds the surplus params to 0,
    the same "missing -> 0" default the rest of the evaluator already uses.

    THE SCC. eval_ast_env, eval_call, bind_params, and build_env now form one
    mutual-recursion cluster. Like the brick-10 evaluator rules they carry
    bound-only termination and ACCEPT the mandatory native recursion breadcrumb:
    each recursive call walks a strict sub-node / shorter tail, but that shrinking
    value is a FIELD of a packed input concept (not the input itself), so the
    structural proof does not fit. The honest backstop is that a call chain's
    length is the SOURCE program's own recursion depth — an interpreter for a
    non-terminating program does not terminate either, which is correct semantics,
    not a soundness gap in this brick.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (all NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line sources, same scan-state
    invocation as items 24/30/31/34/35). A new eval_main driver evaluates the
    FIRST rule's body (the entry point, like `main`) with the program threaded so
    its calls resolve: `main: out = double(21)` + `double(x): out = x * 2` -> 42;
    `add(20, 22)` + `add(x, y): out = x + y` -> 42 (two params); `f(10)` +
    `f(n): let d = n * 2 / out = d + 1` -> 21 (callee with a let); `double(inc(20))`
    -> 42 (a call as an argument, evaluated in the caller env); and the proof it is
    a real interpreter — `fact(5)` + `fact(n): out = if n == 0 then 1 else n *
    fact(n - 1)` -> 120 (RECURSIVE, the call chain firing through eval_call ->
    eval_ast_env -> AstCall -> eval_call until the base case). The existing
    eval_block / eval_nth_rule / eval_rule_decl drivers thread an empty program
    (RuleList::RNil), so a bare block or single rule with a call hits the find_rule
    sentinel -> 0, exactly the old behavior — fully backward compatible.

37. Brick 19 of the self-hosting arc: a TYPE CHECKER in Verbose — the static
    pendant of item 36's interpreter. Where the interpreter computes a VALUE for
    an AST, the type checker computes a TYPE: a small lattice {number, bool,
    text, ERROR} encoded as non-negative codes (0 = number, 1 = bool, 2 = text
    since brick 30, 3 = ERROR). type_check(source) returns the total
    number of type errors (ill-typed let RHSs + ill-typed rule results) across
    the whole program; 0 = well-typed.

    NON-NEGATIVE CODES. A -1 sentinel would let the optimizer (default field
    range [0, i32::MAX]) dead-eliminate any `x < 0` branch, so every type code is
    >= 0 and the classifiers compare against the literal codes 0/1/3 directly.

    THE TYPE ENVIRONMENT. The brick-10 Env concept is REUSED as the type env:
    each ECons stores a name span and, in `val`, the bound name's TYPE code.
    env_lookup works UNCHANGED — it returns the stored type code on a match, 0
    (= number) on an unbound name, which is the right default for an unannotated
    parameter (the interpreter's all-numbers world). build_tenv mirrors build_env:
    fold the lets in source order, typing each RHS against the env built so far,
    consing (name span, RHS type) on the front so later lets see earlier ones.

    TYPING RULES (v1). AstNum => number; AstBool => bool; AstStr => text (brick
    30); AstErr/AstField => ERROR; AstVar => env_lookup; AstCall => number. AstNeg requires a number
    operand, AstNot a bool operand. AstBin: arithmetic (+ - * / %) needs both
    number => number; ORDERING (< > <= >=) needs both number => bool (ordering
    booleans is not meaningful); EQUALITY (== !=) accepts two operands of the SAME
    comparable type — number==number OR bool==bool — and yields bool (brick 29;
    text==text is still ERROR — a string literal types as text since brick 30, but
    text supports no operations); logic (and/or) needs both
    bool => bool. AstIf: bool condition AND both branches the same non-ERROR type
    => that type, else ERROR. Any mismatch => ERROR.

    THE SCC. type_of_env + build_tenv (+ the per-rule tcheck_binds) form a
    recursive group/text cluster exactly like the interpreter's eval_ast_env +
    build_env: each recursive call walks a strict sub-node / shorter tail, but
    that shrinking value is a FIELD of a packed input concept, so the structural
    proof does not fit — bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb,
    same as item 36. Backstops: finite Env / binding / rule lists and a finite
    AST bounded by max_nodes.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (all NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line sources, same scan-state
    invocation as items 24/30/31/34/35/36). A type_check driver folds the check
    over the parsed program: `out = 1 + 2` -> 0; `out = 1 + (2 < 3)` -> 1
    (number + bool); `out = if 5 then 1 else 2` -> 1 (non-bool condition);
    `out = if 1 < 2 then 3 else 4` -> 0 (bool condition, number branches); the
    showcase `let b = 1 < 2 / out = if b then 1 else 2` -> 0 (b inferred bool
    from its RHS, so using it as a condition is well-typed — proves the type
    environment works) vs `let n = 5 / out = if n then 1 else 2` -> 1 (n is
    number, used as a condition -> error); `out = (1 < 2) and (3 < 4)` -> 0
    (bool and bool) vs `out = (1 < 2) and 3` -> 1 (and with a number operand);
    and a two-rule program with one good and one bad rule -> 1.

38. Brick 20 of the self-hosting arc: TYPED PARAMETERS. Brick 16 parsed a rule's
    formals as bare name spans (PCons of name_start, name_len, rest); brick 20
    teaches the parameter parser the OPTIONAL type annotation `IDENT : TYPENAME`,
    recording each parameter's declared TYPE alongside its name. There is no `->`
    token in the tokenizer, so the annotation uses a `:` colon (op code 10) — the
    same colon the header `logic:` uses — never a return-type arrow.

    THE GRAMMAR. A parameter is `IDENT` (untyped) OR `IDENT : TYPENAME`. In the
    token stream the typed form is THREE tokens (name, `:`, typename) before the
    `,` (op 11) or `)` (op 22) separator; the untyped form is ONE token. TYPENAME
    is an Ident mapped to a TYPE CODE by type_code_of_span: "number" -> 0, "bool"
    -> 1, "text" -> 2 (the SAME codes brick 19 assigns), and anything else -> 0
    (default number) — so an unrecognized type name degrades gracefully to number,
    matching the rest of the header parse's fail-graceful posture. An untyped
    parameter also defaults to ty = 0, so `rule f(x)` and `rule f(x : number)`
    carry the IDENTICAL ParamList.

    THE CONCEPT CHANGE. ParamList's PCons gains a `ty : number` field
    (name_start, name_len, ty, rest). Every PCons construct/match site is updated:
    params_prepend / params_scan (build), bind_params / param_list_len /
    param_to_binding (match). params_scan is rewritten to detect the colon at
    pos+1, read the typename at pos+2, and dispatch the separator from pos+3 (typed)
    or pos+1 (untyped); the untyped path reduces EXACTLY to brick 16's behavior, so
    untyped lists parse byte-identically and every downstream consumer (the
    arity-count linter, the call/apply evaluator's parameter binding) is unchanged.
    type_code_of_span is the flat fixed-width byte-check sibling of span_is_rule /
    span_is_logic.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line sources, same scan-state invocation
    as items 24/30/31/34-37). nth_param_type(source, n) tokenizes, parses the
    program, takes the FIRST rule's parameter list, and returns the type code of
    its n-th parameter (0-based; the index n is carried in the scan state's pos),
    sentinel 9 when n runs past the end: `rule add(x : number, y : bool)` at n=0
    -> 0, n=1 -> 1; `rule f(a : text, b : number, c : bool)` at n=0 -> 2, n=1 -> 0,
    n=2 -> 1; `rule g(x)` (untyped) at n=0 -> 0 (default number); `rule h()` (no
    params) at n=0 -> 9 (sentinel); `rule m(a : bool, b)` (mixed) at n=0 -> 1,
    n=1 -> 0. param_nth_type walks the PCons tail via a DECREASING Number field
    (n -> n - 1), so its termination is proved mechanically (Phase C), like
    drop_rules over a RuleList.

39. Brick 21 of the self-hosting arc: CALL-SITE ARGUMENT TYPE checking — where
    the parser (brick 20 typed params) and the type checker (brick 19) finally
    meet. The callee pass (brick 15) asks "does the called rule EXIST?"; the arity
    pass (brick 17) asks "does it pass the RIGHT NUMBER of arguments?"; this pass
    asks "does each argument's TYPE match the callee's DECLARED parameter type?".
    A call f(1 < 2) to a rule `rule f(x : number)` is fine for the callee pass (f
    exists) and the arity pass (1 arg, 1 param) but WRONG here — a bool flows into
    a number parameter.

    ORTHOGONAL to brick 19's type_check, with the same no-double-counting discipline
    that separates lint_arity from lint_callees: an argument whose OWN type is
    already ERROR (3) is brick 19's concern and is SKIPPED here; a WELL-typed
    argument of the WRONG type is what this pass flags. argtype_check(source) sums,
    over the whole program, the count of call-site arguments whose type mismatches
    the callee's param.

    TYPING THE ARGUMENT. The caller's type env is seeded with the caller's OWN
    params at their declared types (param_to_tenv — the type-env sibling of brick
    16's param_to_binding) THEN extended with its let bindings (brick 19's
    build_tenv). So an argument referencing a typed param of the caller is typed
    correctly. THE SHOWCASE: `rule g(b : bool) ... out = f(b)` with `rule f(x :
    number)` flags `b` (bool by g's declaration, passed to f's number param); the
    `b : number` version flags nothing.

    THE LOCKSTEP. Per call, walk the argument list (ArgCons tail) and the callee's
    param list (ptail) together; for each (arg, param) pair count a mismatch iff
    the param exists (phead_ty != 9) AND arg type != param type AND arg type != 3.
    When one list runs out, pairing stops (count mismatches are lint_arity's
    concern). Untyped params default to number (0), so a bool to an untyped param
    IS flagged (documented). The callee is resolved with find_rule (brick 18); on
    no match the sentinel MkRule has PNil params -> no pairs -> no arg-type errors
    (lint_callees flags the missing callee). A call's RESULT type stays number (0)
    — no return-type syntax yet — so type_of_env is unchanged; this is a SEPARATE
    counting pass (argtype_ast / argtype_args / argtype_binds, mirroring the
    count_badcall_* walk and the iter/all split of lint_callees_list).

    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line sources, same scan-state invocation
    as items 24/30/31/34-38): f(5)->f(x:number) -> 0; f(1<2)->f(x:number) -> 1;
    f(1<2)->f(x:bool) -> 0; g(b:bool)->f(x:number) -> 1 (showcase);
    g(b:number)->f(x:number) -> 0; add(5, 1<2) with two number params -> 1;
    add(1<2, 3<4) -> 2; f(g(1<2)) with both rules number-param'd -> 1 (g's inner
    bool arg flagged, f's call-typed arg is number); h(1<2) with h undefined -> 0
    (sentinel skip). The recursive walk SCC (argtype_ast/args/binds) carries
    bound-only termination + the native recursion breadcrumb, like type_of_env.

40. check_program(source) -> total diagnostic count across ALL analyses (brick 22).
    THE FULL PIPELINE — the self-hosting compiler's main(). Every prior driver
    re-tokenizes and re-parses on its own; this one tokenizes and parses EXACTLY
    ONCE, then runs all five analyses over the single shared RuleList and sums
    their diagnostics. The five: lint_list (undefined vars + use-before-def,
    bricks 13/14), lint_callees_list (undefined callees, brick 15), lint_arity_list
    (wrong arg count, brick 17), tcheck_list (ill-typed expressions, brick 19),
    argtype_list (call-arg type mismatches, brick 21). The categories are
    orthogonal by construction (an undefined callee is not an arity error; an arg
    that is itself ill-typed is type_check's concern, not argtype's), so the sum
    double-counts nothing — every diagnostic is one unit. 0 iff the program passes
    every check the compiler knows how to make.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line, same scan-state invocation as the
    other drivers): clean add+main program -> 0; `out = x + y` (x,y undefined) -> 2;
    `out = 1 + (2 < 3)` -> 1; `out = g(1)` (g undefined) -> 1; f(a) called f(1,2)
    -> 1 (arity); f(x:number) whose body is `out = z` AND called with f(1<2) -> 2
    (undefined z + bool arg to number param — two categories in one program). This
    is the closest thing yet to verbosec written in Verbose: lex, parse, and verify
    in one call. check_program reuses every list-rule unchanged (one parse, all
    checks) — bound 256, calls the five list-rules over the shared prog.

41. first_bad_rule(source) / first_bad_category(source) -> a STRUCTURED diagnostic
    (brick 23). check_program collapses the whole program to a single error COUNT —
    a pass/fail gate that cannot say WHERE the program is wrong. This brick localizes
    the FIRST failure: rule_category(rule) returns which analysis fails first for one
    rule, in a fixed precedence order (the earliest failing analysis wins, so a rule
    with several problems reports exactly one):
      0 = clean
      1 = undefined variable / use-before-def   (lint_rule)
      2 = undefined callee                       (badcall_rule)
      3 = wrong arity                            (badarity_rule)
      4 = ill-typed expression                   (tcheck_rule)
      5 = call-argument type mismatch            (argtype_rule)
    find_diag(prog) then walks the rule list with a running 0-based index and returns
    the FIRST rule whose category is nonzero, as a Diag { rule_index, category }; a
    fully clean program yields Diag { rule_index: 9999, category: 0 } (9999 = "no bad
    rule"). Diag is a single-variant group concept (MkDiag) — like RuleDecl/Block —
    so find_diag returns it through the SAME group-return ABI as find_rule (returns a
    RuleDecl) and build_env (returns an Env); the bare-group accessors diag_index /
    diag_cat read one field off it (same idiom as rd_body / block_binds). The two
    drivers expose the two fields to argv.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line; pairs are (rule_index, category)):
    clean add+main -> (9999, 0); a/b where b's body is `out = x` -> (1, 1);
    `out = g(1)` (g undefined) in rule 0 -> (0, 2); f(a) then main calls f(1,2)
    -> (1, 3); `out = 1 + (2 < 3)` in rule 0 -> (0, 4); main calls f(1<2) with f a
    number-param rule -> (0, 5); precedence — f(x:number) whose body is `out = z`
    AND main calls f(1<2): the undefined z in rule 0 (category 1) is reported BEFORE
    main's arg-type at index 1 -> (0, 1); ordering — a/b clean, c's body `out = w`
    -> (2, 1). first_bad_rule/_category reuse the five per-rule analyses unchanged,
    composing them the way check_program composes the five list-rules.

42. all_diags_count(source) / nth_diag_at_rule(source, n) / nth_diag_at_cat(source, n)
    -> the COMPLETE diagnostic report (brick 24). Brick 23's find_diag stops at the
    FIRST failing rule and returns one Diag; this brick walks the WHOLE program and
    builds a DiagList — a cons-list with ONE Diag per (rule, failing-category) pair.
    A rule that is undefined-AND-ill-typed yields TWO entries (category 1 then 4); a
    clean rule contributes nothing. Within a rule the categories appear in ascending
    order (1..5); rules in source order. The five per-rule analyses (lint_rule=1,
    badcall_rule=2, badarity_rule=3, tcheck_rule=4, argtype_rule=5) are reused
    verbatim — the same five rule_category composes in brick 23, but here EVERY
    nonzero category is kept, not just the first.
      rule_diags(rule, idx) -> the DiagList of one rule, ascending order, built by a
        non-recursive let-chain (tail first: d5, then d4..d1, so category 1 ends at
        the front). diag_append(a, b) -> standard cons-list append (a's diags in front
        of b's). prog_diags(prog) -> walk the program, appending each rule's diags
        before the rest's, threading the running 0-based index. diag_count(list) -> the
        list LENGTH. nth_diag_rule(list, n) / nth_diag_cat(list, n) -> the n-th diag's
        rule index (sentinel 9999) / category (sentinel 0).
    DiagList is a 2-variant group cons-list (DCons|DNil) — like Binding/ArgList/RuleList
    — returned through the same group-return ABI as build_env returning an Env.

    GRANULARITY (the headline distinction from brick 22): diag_count counts (rule,
    category) PAIRS, NOT individual problems. A rule with TWO undefined variables is
    ONE diag (category 1 present once), whereas check_program counts it as 2. So
    all_diags_count <= check_program in general; they coincide only when no rule has
    multiple instances of one category. DiagList is a CATEGORIZED report (where +
    what-kind); check_program is a raw problem TALLY.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line; pairs are (rule_index, category)):
    clean add+main -> count 0; `out = x + y` (two undef vars, one rule) -> count 1,
    nth(0)=(0,1) [check_program on the same = 2 — the granularity contrast];
    `out = z + (1 < 2)` -> count 2, nth(0)=(0,1), nth(1)=(0,4); a/b with bodies
    `out = x` / `out = y` -> count 2, nth(0)=(0,1), nth(1)=(1,1); QUAD —
    f(a:number) body `out = z + 1` AND main body `out = f(1 < 2, 3) + g(9)` -> count
    4, nth(0)=(0,1), nth(1)=(1,2), nth(2)=(1,3), nth(3)=(1,5).

43. undef_span_start_of(source) / undef_span_len_of(source) / undef_span_char(source)
    -> COLUMN-LEVEL location for undefined variables (brick 25). Bricks 13/14 COUNTED
    undefined-variable references (lint_rule -> a number); this brick walks the SAME
    traversal in the SAME scope discipline but returns the (start, len) SPAN of the
    FIRST unbound variable — the byte range a diagnostic points AT, instead of a tally.
    The undef_span_* family mirrors count_undef_* arm-for-arm, swapping the count's
    "+ (sum)" for span_or ("first non-sentinel wins"): in the count, two subtrees'
    counts ADD; here the leftmost real span WINS. The sentinel "no undefined variable"
    span is MkSpan(9999, 0).
      Span is a single-variant group concept (MkSpan(start, len)) — like Diag (MkDiag)
        — returned through the same group-return ABI as find_diag returning a Diag.
      span_start(s) / span_len(s) -> bare-group accessors (like diag_index / diag_cat).
      span_or(a, b) -> the first Span whose start is not 9999 (the no-result sentinel).
      undef_span_ast / undef_span_args -> mutually recursive AST walk; AstVar(start,len)
        yields its span when name_bound == 0, else the sentinel; children combine
        left-to-right via span_or (AstBin lhs before rhs, AstIf cond/thn/els, call args
        head before tail). undef_span_binds -> each let RHS checked against the PREFIX
        of earlier bindings (use-before-def), RHS before the tail. undef_span_rule ->
        bindings (params as base prefix) checked BEFORE the result (params appended to
        the full scope). undef_span_list -> head rule before tail (program order).
    TRAVERSAL ORDER matches count_undef exactly, so the first span found is the first
    the count would have tallied: within a rule the let RHSs precede the result; within
    an expression left-to-right; across rules program order.

    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line; reported as (start, len, char), char =
    byte_at(source, start) = the offending name's first byte):
    clean add+main -> start 9999, len 0, char ABORTS (native byte_at is fail-closed on
    an OOB index — there is no first byte of a name that does not exist; test
    cleanliness via undef_span_start_of == 9999, not the char);
    `out = x + y` -> char 120 ('x'), len 1 (lhs of +, leftmost);
    `out = 1 + y` -> char 121 ('y'), len 1 (1 is a leaf, y is the first var);
    `out = foo + 1` -> char 102 ('f'), len 3 (name "foo");
    `let p = q + 1` / `let q = 2` / `out = p` -> char 113 ('q'), len 1 (q unbound in p's
    RHS; binding RHSs checked before the result, q not yet in the prefix);
    a `out = 1` / b `out = zzz` -> char 122 ('z'), len 3 (rule 1's zzz; rule 0 clean);
    main `out = f(w)` / f(x:number) `out = x` -> char 119 ('w'), len 1 (w undefined in
    main; f's param x is in scope only inside f).

44. nth_diag_at_span_start(source, n) / nth_diag_at_span_len(source, n) -> the LOCATED
    full report (brick 26). Brick 24 reported the COMPLETE diagnostic list (one Diag per
    rule-category pair) but every Diag only said WHICH rule and WHAT KIND; brick 25
    found the SPAN of the first undefined variable but only as a standalone driver, not
    threaded into the report. This brick joins the two: the Diag record (MkDiag) is
    WIDENED with two number fields — span_start / span_len — and rule_diags POPULATES
    them for the undefined-variable category (1) via undef_span_rule. So the full report
    now points AT the offending token, not just at the rule.
      MkDiag(rule_index, category, span_start, span_len) -> brick 23's two fields plus
        the new span. diag_span_start(d) / diag_span_len(d) -> the matching bare-group
        accessors (mirrors of diag_index / diag_cat).
      LOCATED ONLY FOR UNDEF: only category 1 (undef-var) carries a real span. Every
        other category (2=undef-callee, 3=arity, 4=ill-typed, 5=arg-type) is a
        whole-rule property, not a name span, so it carries the sentinel (start 9999,
        len 0): "not located". find_diag's summary Diag also stays sentinel-spanned —
        the located report is the DiagList, not the single-Diag summary.
      rule_diags computes usp = undef_span_rule(...) ONCE above the d5..d1 chain (cheap +
        pure; only USED when category 1 fires), then d1's MkDiag fills its span from
        span_start(usp) / span_len(usp); d2..d5 keep the sentinel.
      nth_diag_span_start / nth_diag_span_len -> walk the DiagList to the n-th cell and
        read diag_span_start / diag_span_len off it (cons-walk idiom, like nth_diag_rule
        / nth_diag_cat); the empty/out-of-bounds case reads the sentinel (9999 / 0).
    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line; spans are whitespace-dependent — the LEN
    and the sentinel are the stable checks):
    `rule f\n  logic:\n    out = foo + 1` -> diag 0 span_start n=0 = 26 (offset of foo),
    span_len n=0 = 3; cross-check undef_span_start_of on the same source = 26;
    quad (undef z in rule 0; callee/arity/argtype in rule 1) -> diag 0 = (rule 0, cat 1,
    LOCATED): span_len n=0 = 1 (z is one char); diags 1/2/3 = cats 2/3/5, span SENTINEL:
    span_start n=1 = 9999, span_len n=1 = 0 (only undef carries a span);
    clean add+main -> empty list: span_start n=0 = 9999, span_len n=0 = 0.

45. badcall_span_rule(rule, program, source) -> the LOCATED undefined-CALLEE diagnostic
    (brick 27). Brick 26 gave the category-1 (undef-var) Diag a real span; every other
    category still said only WHICH rule and WHAT KIND. This brick extends the located
    report to category 2 (undef-callee): the category-2 Diag now points AT the offending
    callee NAME, exactly as category 1 points at the offending variable name.
      badcall_span_ast / badcall_span_args / badcall_span_binds / badcall_span_rule ->
        the Span-returning analogue of the count_badcall_* family (brick "category 2").
        Each mirrors its count twin arm-for-arm, swapping "+ (sum)" for span_or and
        returning the first bad callee's NAME span instead of a count. Traversal order
        matches count_badcall: binds before result, left-to-right within an expression,
        and the OUTER call's callee BEFORE its args (so for g(h(1)) with g undefined, g's
        span wins; with g defined and h undefined, the args walk reports h's span).
      SIMPLER THAN undef_span_rule: undefined-callee scope is program-wide, so
        badcall_span_rule builds NO param scope and threads NO binding prefix — it just
        checks the binds then the result, both against the same program rule list (the
        same shape as badcall_rule for the count). The AstCall arm reports the callee
        span IMMEDIATELY when rule_named == 0; it only descends into the args when the
        callee exists.
      rule_diags computes csp = badcall_span_rule(...) ONCE above the d5..d1 chain (same
        cheap + pure shape as brick 26's usp; only USED when category 2 fires), then d2's
        MkDiag fills its span from span_start(csp) / span_len(csp); d3/d4/d5 keep the
        sentinel (9999 / 0), and d1 stays as brick 26 left it.
    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line; the LEN and the sentinel are the stable
    checks since spans are whitespace-dependent):
    `rule main\n  logic:\n    out = g(1)` -> all_diags_count 1; cat n=0 = 2; span_len n=0 = 1
    (g is one char); span_start n=0 = offset of g.
    `rule main\n  logic:\n    out = foobar(1)` -> cat n=0 = 2; span_len n=0 = 6.
    quad (undef z in rule 0; f(...) clean + undefined g in rule 1) -> diag 1 (cat 2) now
    LOCATED: cat n=1 = 2, span_len n=1 = 1 (was 0 before this brick — g is one char),
    span_start n=1 = offset of g (was 9999); diag 0 (undef z) UNCHANGED: cat n=0 = 1,
    span_len n=0 = 1; diag 2 (cat 3 arity) STILL sentinel: span_len n=2 = 0,
    span_start n=2 = 9999.

46. badarity_span_rule(rule, program, source) -> the LOCATED arity-mismatch diagnostic
    (brick 28). Bricks 26/27 located categories 1 (undef-var) and 2 (undef-callee); this
    brick extends the located report to category 3 (arity): the category-3 Diag now points
    AT the offending CALL's callee NAME, exactly as category 2 points at an undefined callee.
      badarity_span_ast / badarity_span_args / badarity_span_binds / badarity_span_rule ->
        the Span-returning analogue of the count_badarity_* family. Each mirrors its count
        twin arm-for-arm, swapping "+ (sum)" for span_or and returning the first arity-
        mismatched call's callee NAME span instead of a count. The per-call decision reuses
        arity_mismatch directly (1 iff the callee EXISTS and its declared param count !=
        this call's arg count). Traversal order matches count_badarity: binds before
        result, left-to-right within an expression, and the OUTER call's own arity BEFORE
        descending into its args.
      SIMPLER THAN undef_span_rule (like badcall_span_rule): arity scope is program-wide,
        so badarity_span_rule builds NO param scope and threads NO binding prefix — it just
        checks the binds then the result, both against the same program rule list (the same
        shape as badarity_rule for the count). The AstCall arm reports the callee span
        IMMEDIATELY when arity_mismatch == 1; it only descends into the args otherwise.
      rule_diags computes asp = badarity_span_rule(...) ONCE above the d5..d1 chain (same
        cheap + pure shape as bricks 26/27's usp/csp; only USED when category 3 fires),
        then d3's MkDiag fills its span from span_start(asp) / span_len(asp); d4/d5 keep the
        sentinel (9999 / 0), and d1/d2 stay as bricks 26/27 left them. Categories 4/5 have
        no single-token name span (AstBin / AstNum carry no source span), so they remain
        unlocated.
    THE MONEY SHOTS (NATIVE-ONLY, multi-line; the LEN and the sentinel are the stable
    checks since spans are whitespace-dependent):
    `rule f(a)\n  logic:\n    out = 1\nrule main\n  logic:\n    out = f(1, 2)` ->
    all_diags_count 1; cat n=0 = 3; span_len n=0 = 1 (f is one char); span_start n=0 = offset
    of the f in the call.
    `rule foobar(a)\n  ...\n    out = foobar(1, 2)` -> cat n=0 = 3; span_len n=0 = 6.
    quad (undef z in rule 0; f(2 args vs 1 param) + undefined g in rule 1) -> diag 2 (cat 3)
    now LOCATED: cat n=2 = 3, span_len n=2 = 1 (was 0 before this brick — f is one char),
    span_start n=2 = offset of f (was 9999); diags 0/1 (cat 1 undef z / cat 2 callee g)
    UNCHANGED located; diag 3 (cat 5 argtype) STILL sentinel: span_len n=3 = 0,
    span_start n=3 = 9999.

47. Brick 29 of the self-hosting arc: EQUALITY ON BOOLEANS in the type system. Brick 19's
    bin_type classified == (op 1) and != (op 6) as number-only (both operands number => bool),
    which wrongly rejected (1 < 2) == (3 < 4). This brick refines ONLY the two equality clauses
    to accept two operands of the SAME comparable type — number==number OR bool==bool — yielding
    bool; anything else (number==bool, or text/ERROR operands) => ERROR. text==text stays ERROR
    (text not yet typed). The ORDERING ops (< > <= >=) stay numeric-only (ordering booleans is
    not meaningful); arithmetic and logic are unchanged. In-place logic tweak to one rule — no
    new concepts/rules. Money shots: (1 < 2) == (3 < 4) => bool (0, was ill-typed before); 1 == 2
    => number==number (0); 1 == (2 < 3) => still ERROR (1); (1 < 2) < (3 < 4) => still ERROR (1,
    ordering on bools); 1 + (2 < 3) => still ERROR (1).

48. Brick 30 of the self-hosting arc: TEXT LITERALS TYPE AS text. Brick 19 typed a
    string-literal expression AstStr as ERROR (3, "text not yet typed"), so a string
    literal passed to a `text` parameter (brick 20 already maps the `text` annotation
    to code 2) was wrongly flagged as a mismatch. This brick changes ONLY the AstStr
    arm of type_of_env from 3 to 2: a string literal is now a first-class text value.
    Text supports no operations — arithmetic/ordering/logic/equality on text all stay
    ERROR via bin_type (unchanged) — so this is a minimal but coherent text type.
    AstField stays ERROR (3, fields still not typed). In-place one-arm logic tweak —
    no new concepts/rules. Money shots: a rule whose body is "hello" => text (0, was
    1 before); a string literal passed to a `text` param => well-typed (argtype 0, was
    1 before); a string literal to a NUMBER param => mismatch (1); a number to a TEXT
    param => mismatch (1); 1 + "x" => still ERROR (1); "a" == "b" => still ERROR (1).

49. Brick 31 of the self-hosting arc: PARSE RETURN-TYPE ANNOTATIONS. After the
    parameter list and before the `logic:` line, a rule header may carry an OPTIONAL
    `: TYPENAME` declaring its return type — `rule add(x : number, y : number) : number`.
    Both header parsers (parse_rule_decl / parse_rule_decl_pos) look at the token right
    after the params: if it is a `:` (op code 10) the next Ident is the return type-name,
    mapped via type_code_of_span (0=number / 1=bool / 2=text); otherwise (a Newline, op 0)
    there is no annotation and the default return type is the sentinel 9 ("unannotated").
    NOTE: brick 31 originally stored the no-annotation default as 0, but brick 33 changed
    it to the sentinel 9 so "no annotation" and explicit ": number" are distinguishable;
    call_result_type maps 9 -> number when typing a call and tcheck_rule's return-vs-body
    check skips unannotated rules. The parsed code is stored in a new
    RuleDecl.MkRule field `return_type` (inserted after params, before body). PARSER-ONLY:
    the return type is recorded but NOT yet consumed by the type checker — feeding it into
    type_of_env needs the whole program threaded through, a later/bigger brick. Mirrors
    brick 20 (typed params). New rules: rd_return_type (accessor), rl_head_return_type
    (head accessor), rule_return_type (money-shot driver). Existing programs without an
    annotation parse byte-identically (after_ret == after_params when there is no `:`).
    Money shots: rule add(x : number, y : number) : number => 0 (number); rule p(x : number)
    : bool => 1 (bool); rule q(x : number) : text => 2 (text); rule r(x : number) (no
    annotation) => 9 (unannotated sentinel — was 0 in brick 31, changed by brick 33);
    rule s() : bool (no params, return type) => 1.

50. Brick 32 of the self-hosting arc: USE RETURN TYPES IN THE TYPE CHECKER. Brick 31
    parsed and stored a rule's declared return type; this brick consumes it. The whole
    program (RuleList) is now threaded through the type checker — TypeArg, BuildTArg,
    TCheckBindsState, TCheckRuleState and TCheckListState each gain a `prog` field, passed
    down every recursive call (the argtype_* family already carried prog since brick 21, so
    its type_of_env / build_tenv calls just pass it). The one behavioral change: type_of_env's
    AstCall arm, which used to yield 0 (assumed number), now yields the callee's DECLARED
    return type via rd_return_type(find_rule(...)). No new recursion is created — find_rule
    walks the RuleList and never calls type_of_env, so the checker's recursion structure is
    unchanged; prog is pure threaded data. An undefined or unannotated callee resolves to the
    find_rule sentinel / default 0 (number), so such calls still type as number (the
    undefined-callee is reported separately by lint_callees). Scope: this brick only makes a
    call's RESULT type correct; it does NOT add a "declared return vs body's inferred type"
    check (that would change diagnostic counts — a later brick). Two payoffs: (1) type errors
    INVOLVING call results are now caught — `rule b() : bool ... out = 1 < 2` then `out = 1 +
    b()` is 1 + bool => type error (was MISSED, since b() used to type as number); (2) false
    positives disappear — `out = if b() then 1 else 2` with b():bool is now well-typed (was a
    false error when b() typed as number, a non-bool condition). Money shots: 1 + b() with
    b():bool => 1; 1 + n() with n():number => 0; if b() with b():bool => 0; 1 + c() with c
    unannotated => 0 (number default); 1 + t() with t():text => 1 (number + text). No new
    concepts or rules (in-place field threading); the existing non-call type checks, the QUAD
    diagnostic report, argtype, check_program and eval are all unchanged.

51. Brick 33 of the self-hosting arc: CHECK A RULE'S DECLARED RETURN TYPE AGAINST ITS
    BODY. Brick 32 made a call's RESULT type correct but deliberately did NOT flag a rule
    whose declared return type disagrees with its body. This brick adds that check. The
    blocker was that brick 31 stored both "no annotation" and explicit ": number" as 0 —
    indistinguishable, so a check would wrongly flag an unannotated rule whose body is
    bool/text (breaking bricks 29/30). Fix: introduce a sentinel — the parser default for
    no annotation becomes 9 ("unannotated"), distinct from explicit ": number" (0). Then
    (a) typing a CALL maps 9 -> number so calls to unannotated rules still type as number
    (preserving brick 32) — done in a new rule call_result_type (input: new concept
    CallRetState) which type_of_env's AstCall arm now delegates to; (b) the return-vs-body
    check fires ONLY when the declared return is explicit (!= 9). In tcheck_rule, after
    typing the result, read the raw declared return (ret = rd_return_type) and add +1 iff
    ret != 9 AND the body is well-typed (result_ty != 3, to avoid double-counting an
    already-ERROR body) AND ret != result_ty. rule_return_type now returns 9 for an
    unannotated rule (was 0). New concept: CallRetState; new rule: call_result_type.
    Money shots: rule b() : bool ... out = 1 < 2 => 0 (matches); rule b() : number ...
    out = 1 < 2 => 1 (declares number, body bool); rule t() : text ... out = 5 => 1;
    rule g() : number ... out = 5 => 0; UNANNOTATED rule f ... out = 1 < 2 => 0 (sentinel
    protects bricks 29/30); UNANNOTATED out = "hello" => 0; src():bool then main():bool
    out = src() => 0 (call result typing + return check compose); same but main():number
    => 1.

52. Brick 34 of the self-hosting arc: THE PRETTY-PRINTER — the FIRST EMITTER over the real
    vexpr AST. Every prior brick CONSUMED the AST (eval, shape, lint, type check); this one
    EMITS it back as source text. print_expr(PrintState{node: Ast, src: text}) walks the tree
    and reconstructs a FULLY-PARENTHESIZED rendering: parens around every AstBin / AstNeg /
    AstNot / AstIf node make the parse's precedence and associativity decisions visible bytes
    ("1 + 2 * 3" prints as "(1 + (2 * 3))", "10 - 2 - 3" as "((10 - 2) - 3)"); no minimal-paren
    logic in v1. Span-carrying leaves (AstVar, AstField's field, AstCall's callee, AstStr)
    print their own source bytes via substring(src, start, start + len) — allocation-free
    pointer slices; AstStr spans include both quotes so string literals reproduce verbatim.
    Number leaves itoa via concat(value); AstBool spells true/false. Operator spelling is
    factored into op_text(OpSpell{op}) — a flat if/else over the 13-code op map, a
    non-recursive text helper legal as a tail concat arg under the streaming v1 grammar.
    Argument lists print without extra parens (print_args bare-first + print_args_rest
    comma-prefixing the rest; ArgNil contributes the empty text — f(1, x) round-trips as
    "f(1, x)", f() as "f()"). Driver print_source = the eval_expr/shape front end (tokenize,
    parse_or from 0, parsed_node) with the printer as body tail. This is the FIRST consumer
    of the native streaming text lowering beyond its acceptance example: natively no string is
    ever materialized — each leaf's bytes stream to stdout in tree-walk order. Termination:
    bound-only + accepted native recursion breadcrumb (node is a FIELD of the packed input,
    so `structural` does not fit — eval_ast_env's posture). Round-trip property, validated
    EXTERNALLY across two binary invocations (the streamed text never exists in memory):
    eval_expr(print_source(s)) == eval_expr(s) (7/5/1 for precedence, left-assoc, comparison)
    and shape(print_source(s)) == shape(s) (20 / 10100 / 100010 for "1 + 2 * 3", "f(1, x)",
    "if 1 < 2 then 3 else 4"). New concepts: PrintState, PrintArgsState, OpSpell; new rules:
    op_text, print_expr, print_args, print_args_rest, print_source.

53. Brick 35 of the self-hosting arc: PRINT A WHOLE PROGRAM — the full-file emitter half.
    Brick 34 printed one expression; this brick prints every layer above it: rule headers
    (name span, typed parameter list, return-type annotation), the `logic:` line, the let
    bindings, and the `out =` result line, with the 2-space / 4-space indentation
    re-synthesized as text literals. Target property: the FULL-FILE round-trip — the printed
    program REPARSES to the same analyses and the same evaluation as the original source:
    eval_main(print_program_src(s)) == eval_main(s), check_program(...) == check_program(s),
    count_rules(...) == count_rules(s). NORMALIZATIONS (deliberate, semantics-preserving —
    the printed form is the parse's canonical spelling): (a) untyped params print with an
    explicit type — brick 20 stores an untyped parameter as ty=0, indistinguishable from an
    explicit `: number`, so the printer always prints `name : <type>` and `rule f(n)` prints
    as `rule f(n : number)` (untyped defaults to number, so every analysis and evaluation
    round-trips); (b) return type: the brick-33 sentinel 9 (UNANNOTATED) prints NOTHING,
    0/1/2 print ` : number` / ` : bool` / ` : text`; (c) PNil prints NO parens — `rule f()`
    normalizes to `rule f` (the parser stores both as PNil); (d) expressions print fully
    parenthesized (brick 34's printer reused); (e) a bare final expression prints in the
    `out = ` form (block_result is the result either way); (f) indentation re-synthesized at
    logic:=2 / statements=4 spaces. IDEMPOTENCE follows: print(parse(print(parse(s)))) ==
    print(parse(s)). Driver print_program_src = the check_program/count_rules/eval_main front
    end (begin_tokenize — a program needs the INDENT/DEDENT stream) with the program printer
    as body tail. Six new text members join brick 34's streaming set (ty_text, ret_text,
    print_params, print_params_rest, print_binds, print_rule, print_program — all text-SCC
    calls in tail concat positions; print_rule's and the driver's lets build number/group
    values only). New concepts: TySpell, PrintParamsState, PrintBindsState, PrintRuleState,
    PrintProgState; new rules: ty_text, ret_text, print_params, print_params_rest,
    print_binds, print_rule, print_program, print_program_src. max_nodes unchanged.

54. Brick 36 of the self-hosting arc: THE FIRST REAL LOWERING (pretty-printer becomes
    code generator). Bricks 34/35 printed the AST back as SOURCE; this brick emits a
    DIFFERENT target — a stack-machine intermediate language in postfix / RPN form.
    `1 + 2 * 3` lowers to `1 2 3 * +`: the canonical first IR of a compiler backend,
    post-order (operands before operator, the opposite of in-order source), requiring a
    stack to evaluate. Reuses the streaming machinery exactly (post-order concat of
    self-calls; same PrintState input = node + src). Rules: op_instr (the postfix
    mnemonic for a binary-op code — bare + trailing space, vs op_text's infix padding),
    lower_expr (post-order: AstBin emits both operands then op_instr; AstNeg/AstNot are
    unary postfix; AstIf -> a 3-operand `select`; AstNum/AstBool push; AstVar -> a named
    `load`; AstCall/AstField/AstStr -> `?`), lower_expr_src (driver: tokenize -> parse_or
    -> lower_expr). VERIFIED END-TO-END by an external RPN/stack evaluator (the
    streaming_lower_rpn_matches_eval_expr test): for the integer-closed subset
    (arithmetic, comparison, logical, neg, not, if->select), run_rpn(lower_expr_src(e))
    == eval_expr(e) — the lowered target computes the SAME value as the interpreter.
    15/15 round-trips incl. division, modulo, and/or, neg, left-assoc, if->select.
    Money shots: lower_expr_src("1 + 2 * 3") = "1 2 3 * + "; "10 - 2 - 3" = "10 2 - 3 - ";
    "if 1 < 2 then 10 else 20" = "1 2 < 10 20 select ". The first Verbose program that
    compiles an expression to a target OTHER than its source. Native-only (streaming).

55. Brick 37 of the self-hosting arc: LOWER A WHOLE PROGRAM to the stack IL (a function
    becomes a callable routine). Brick 36 lowered one expression; this lowers every rule.
    Calling convention: a routine is `proc NAME p1 p2 ... <body ops> ret`; a call site
    emits its argument ops (left to right) then `call NAME` (NO argc — the VM reads the
    callee proc's param count); the VM pops that many values, binds them to the callee's
    params by position into a fresh frame, runs the routine, and `ret` leaves the return
    value on the stack. `let NAME = expr` lowers to `<value ops> store NAME` sharing the
    frame's name->value map with the params, so `load NAME` resolves either.
    IMPORTANT — brick 37 GENERALIZES brick 36's eager 3-operand `select` to the structured
    LAZY `if`/`else`/`endif` (only the taken branch runs; the VM skips regions with
    nesting-aware depth matching, no labels). This is what makes RECURSION terminate:
    factorial's `else n * fact(n-1)` is NOT evaluated when n == 0, so `select` (which
    evaluates both arms) would have looped forever. lower_expr's AstIf and AstCall arms
    changed accordingly; the brick-36 expression round-trip test's VM was updated to the
    if/else/endif form (still 15/15). New rules: lower_args (call args, no separators —
    the stack carries the boundary), lower_params (bare param names for the proc header),
    lower_binds (let -> store), lower_rule (proc header + binds + body + ret; accessors
    hoisted into lets exactly like print_rule, since inline nested accessor calls in a
    streaming concat hit the recursive-match number-emit limitation), lower_program (one
    proc per rule), lower_program_src (driver: begin_tokenize -> parse_program ->
    lower_program). VERIFIED END-TO-END by an IL VM (named procs, a call stack with
    per-frame param/let bindings, structured lazy if/else/endif) — the
    streaming_lower_program_matches_eval_main test: run_il(lower_program_src(p), first_proc)
    == eval_main(p). 4/4 incl. recursive factorial -> 120, double(add(3,4)) -> 14 (nested
    calls), sq(5) with a let -> 26, fib(10) -> 55 (double recursion). Money shot:
    lower_program_src(factorial) = "proc main \n5 call fact ret\nproc fact n \nload n 0 ==
    if 1 else load n load n 1 - call fact * endif ret\n". The first Verbose program that
    compiles a multi-rule PROGRAM to a target other than its source. Native-only (streaming).
    Existing binaries byte-identical (the if/else/endif change + new rules leak into no
    non-streaming path). Streaming gap found + worked around (not a compiler change): a
    recursive number-returning rule (arg_list_len) used as a concat number arg in a
    streaming body hits emit_eval_expr's "MatchVariant A.4.1 scrutinee = Call only" limit;
    dropped argc from the IL (the VM infers arity from the proc header), which also made
    the IL cleaner.

56. Backend brick b3 (milestone of the backend arc): LOWER A CLOSED EXPRESSION TO REAL
    x86-64 MACHINE CODE. Brick 36's lower_expr lowered an AST to a TEXT RPN stream; b3
    lowers the SAME tree to BYTES — actual x86-64 instructions a CPU executes. Reuses
    PrintState (node + src) and the same post-order recursion, but each arm emits b"..."
    opcodes (brick b1) composed with concat / le64 (brick b2) instead of mnemonic text.
    The emitted bytes are a function fn() -> i64: it evaluates the expression onto the
    CPU's own hardware stack (push/pop balanced), leaves the result in rax, and ret's —
    no prologue, no rbp frame. The hardware stack IS the RPN stack. Verified subset
    (branchless + fault-free): AstNum, AstBin with op in {13 +, 14 -, 15 *}, AstNeg. NO
    div/mod (idiv faults), NO comparisons/logic (need setcc), NO if (computed offsets),
    NO vars/calls — b3-followups. Out-of-subset ops/variants emit a single int3 trap byte
    (CC) so a miscompile faults loudly. Instruction selection: AstNum(v) => mov rax,
    <v:imm64> (48 B8 + le64 v) ; push rax (50). AstBin(op,l,r) => <code l> <code r> ; pop
    rcx (59) ; pop rax (58) ; {add 48 01 C8 | sub 48 29 C8 | imul 48 0F AF C1} ; push rax
    (50). AstNeg(inner) => <code inner> ; pop rax (58) ; neg rax (48 F7 D8) ; push rax
    (50). pop rcx ; pop rax puts the RIGHT operand (pushed last, on top) in rcx and LEFT
    in rax, so sub computes left-right in source order. Rules: x86_expr (the byte code
    generator, same shape as lower_expr but bytes leaves), x86_expr_src (driver: tokenize
    -> parse_or -> parsed_node -> x86_expr, then append pop rax (58) ; ret (C3)).
    STATUS: both rules added and the verifier accepts them (119 concepts / 261 rules, all
    proofs check). NATIVE LOWERING IS NOT YET BUILT: x86_expr is recursive (over the AST,
    plus the driver chain through skip_spaces / parse_or), and the recursive native path
    refuses Bytes output ("recursive rule output must be Number, Bool, or Text"). The
    streaming-emit machinery that lets the recursive TEXT twin (lower_expr_src) compile is
    wired for Type::Text only; an emit_streaming_*_body path for Bytes leaves (Expr::Bytes,
    le32/le64, bytes-concat) plus lifting the recursive-output gate to Bytes is needed —
    a src change in the native backend, deferred pending scope confirmation. Intended
    end-to-end verification (streaming_x86_expr_executes): mmap the emitted bytes RWX, call
    as fn() -> i64, assert == eval_expr(e) for "1 + 2"(3), "1 + 2 * 3"(7), "10 - 2 - 3"(5),
    "2 * 3 * 4"(24), "- 5 + 2"(-3), "(1 + 2) * (3 + 4)"(21), "100 - 50 * 2"(0), "7"(7).

57. Backend brick b4a: COMPARISONS + if/else in the machine-code generator — REAL
    CONDITIONAL BRANCHES (jcc with COMPUTED relative offsets). The control-flow
    prerequisite for lowering recursive programs (b4b). b3 emitted only branchless,
    fault-free arithmetic; b4a adds the six comparisons and the if construct, which
    means the first computed jump distances in any Verbose-emitted machine code.
    The core challenge: a jcc/jmp rel32 needs the byte distance to its target, but a
    streaming emitter writes left-to-right and cannot backpatch. So a new rule
    code_size_expr(ps) returns the EXACT byte count x86_expr(ps) emits for a subtree,
    computed structurally over the AST (pure arithmetic — it never calls x86_expr or
    le32). if emits its jz/jmp with offsets derived from code_size_expr of the
    branches; any mismatch = wrong offset = crash/wrong result, caught by mmap+exec.
    Instruction selection. Comparison (op 1 ==, 6 !=, 19 <, 20 >, 5 <=, 4 >=), after
    both operands are pushed: pop rcx (59) ; pop rax (58) ; cmp rax,rcx (48 39 C8) ;
    setcc al (0F 9X C0 — sete 94 / setne 95 / setl 9C / setg 9F / setle 9E / setge 9D) ;
    movzx eax,al (0F B6 C0) ; push rax (50) — 12 bytes after the operands. AstIf(cond,
    thn,els) => <code cond> (leaves 0/1) ; pop rax (58) ; test rax,rax (48 85 C0) ; jz
    rel32 (0F 84 + le32(code_size_expr(thn)+5)) ; <code thn> ; jmp rel32 (E9 +
    le32(code_size_expr(els))) ; <code els>. The jz skips thn + the 5-byte jmp; the jmp
    skips els. Both branches leave exactly one value on the stack and control merges
    after els, so an if composes as a sub-expression like any other pushed value.
    code_size_expr arms (MUST equal x86_expr byte length): AstNum 11; +/- l+r+6; * l+r+7;
    cmp l+r+12; unknown op l+r+1 (the int3 trap CC); AstNeg inner+5; AstIf cond+15+thn+els
    (pop 1 + test 3 + jz 6 + jmp 5); out-of-subset leaves 1 (CC). div/mod and and/or stay
    OUT (idiv faults; logic needs more) — later. STATUS: verified (262 rules); both new
    arms + code_size_expr added; x86_expr_src compiles natively via b3's recursive
    streaming-bytes path (NO src change). Verified end-to-end (streaming_x86_if_cmp_executes):
    mmap RWX, call fn() -> i64, assert == eval_expr(e) for "1 < 2"(1), "2 < 1"(0),
    "3 == 3"(1), "3 != 3"(0), "5 >= 5"(1), "2 * 3 > 5"(1), "if 1 < 2 then 10 else 20"(10),
    "if 0 then 1 else 2"(2), "if 2 * 3 == 6 then 100 else 200"(100), "if (1 + 1) < 2 then 7
    else if 3 > 2 then 8 else 9"(8, nested if in else — exercises offset math), and
    "(if 1 < 2 then 3 else 4) * 10"(30, if as a sub-expression).

58. Brick b4b-1 of the backend arc: lower a whole NON-RECURSIVE multi-rule PROGRAM to ONE
    callable x86-64 machine-code blob. b3/b4a lowered a closed expression (with control flow);
    this lowers procs that CALL each other, with a frame ABI for params and real call/ret.
    The blob is mmap'd executable and called at the entry proc (first rule, offset 0) as
    fn()->i64; mmap+exec == eval_main. VERBOSE-ONLY (no native streaming-core change — reuses
    the b1/b2 streaming-bytes path).

    Calling convention: caller lowers each arg (left to right, value on the CPU stack), then
    `call rel32` (e8) ; `add rsp, 8*N` (48 81 c4, pop args) ; `push rax` (callee result).
    Proc prologue `push rbp ; mov rbp,rsp` (55 48 89 e5); param i (decl order) at
    [rbp + 16 + 8*(N-1-i)], loaded `push qword [rbp+disp]` (ff b5 + disp32); epilogue
    `pop rax ; mov rsp,rbp ; pop rbp ; ret` (58 48 89 ec 5d c3). Entry proc has 0 params.

    The cross-proc `call rel32` needs absolute positions, which a streaming emitter can't
    backpatch — solved with a POSITION-THREADED codegen: a new ByteGenState{ node, src, off,
    params, prog } carries `off` = the absolute byte offset where this subtree's code begins;
    siblings advance off by code_size_node (the byte-exact size rule, mirror of code_size_expr
    incl. AstVar=6, AstCall=args+13). proc_size(rule)=4+code_size(body)+6; proc_offset walks
    the RuleList summing earlier proc_sizes; a call's rel32 = proc_offset(callee) - (off +
    code_size_args + 5). New rules: x86_node/x86_args/code_size_node/code_size_args/param_index/
    proc_size/proc_offset/x86_proc/x86_program/x86_program_src (the closed-expr x86_expr path is
    kept separate + unchanged). AstVar not among params, lets, div/mod/logic -> int3 trap
    (out of subset).

    Verified (streaming_x86_program_executes, all blob mmap+exec == eval_main == hand value):
    double(add(3,4))->14; f(2,g(3)) with f(a,b)=a*b,g(n)=n+1 ->8 (nested call as arg);
    sub(10,3)=a-b ->7 (param order, non-commutative); h(n)=n*n on 5 ->25 (same param twice);
    if cmp(2,3) then 100 else 200, cmp(a,b)=a<b ->100 (call result inside a b4a if). NEXT
    (b4b-2): recursion — a proc calling itself (factorial) -> 120, composing this + b4a's if.

59. Brick b4b-2 of the backend arc: RECURSION in Verbose-emitted x86-64 machine code — the
    backend-arc milestone. No new Verbose code: b4b-1's program lowering (proc layout, frame
    ABI, real call/ret) composes with b4a's if/comparison to give recursion for FREE. A proc's
    self-call resolves through proc_offset to its OWN offset, so the `call rel32` is a backward
    jump; the if/else base case terminates it; the frame ABI holds the param per recursion
    level. Verified (streaming_x86_program_recursion_executes): each blob mmap+exec == eval_main:
    fact(5)->120, fact(10)->3628800, fib(10)->55 (double recursion), mutual even/odd ev(10)->1,
    linear sum rec(5)->15. A compiler written in Verbose emits native machine code for recursive
    AND mutually-recursive programs, and it runs. (div/mod/logic/lets still out — followups.)

60. Brick b5 of the backend arc: WRAP THE BLOB IN A STANDALONE ELF EXECUTABLE. b4b lowered a
    program to a position-independent machine-code blob (entry proc at offset 0, value in rax).
    b5 wraps that blob in a minimal static ELF64 + a 17-byte `_start` trampoline so the OUTPUT
    IS A RUNNABLE FILE: `elf_program_src "...prog..." 0 > a.out ; chmod +x a.out ; ./a.out ;
    echo $?` prints the entry proc's value as the process exit code. A compiler written in
    Verbose that produces a runnable native binary. Layout (load-from-offset-0 static ELF, base
    0x400000): [ELF64 header 64 B] [one PT_LOAD program header 56 B] [_start trampoline 17 B]
    [program blob]. The single PT_LOAD maps the whole file at 0x400000 R+X; entry = base + 120
    (the trampoline, right after the 120 header bytes); the blob starts at file offset 137
    (120 + 17). The trampoline is `call rel32 = 12` (reaches the first proc at 137 - 125),
    `mov rdi, rax` (returned value -> exit-code register), `mov rax, 60` (sys_exit), `syscall`.
    The ONLY computed header field is p_filesz = p_memsz = 137 + program_total_size(prog),
    emitted via le64 — every other header byte is a fixed b"..." literal. New Verbose:
    program_total_size (sum of proc_size over every rule) + elf_program_src (the driver). Exit
    codes are 0..255, so the milestone tests results < 256 (printing arbitrary i64 needs
    itoa-in-machine-code, a later brick). Verified (streaming_elf_program_runs): the emitted
    file's CHILD EXIT CODE == eval_main(program) for fact(5)->120, fib(10)->55, sum rec(5)->15,
    mutual even/odd ev(10)->1, double(add(3,4))->14, and the constant `out = 7`->7.

61. Brick b6 of the backend arc: the FOUR MISSING BINARY OPERATORS in the machine-code generator
    — division `/` (op 16), modulo `%` (op 17), logical `and` (op 30), logical `or` (op 31).
    b3/b4a/b4b emitted +,-,*,neg, the 6 comparisons, if/else, calls and recursion; b6 fills the
    arithmetic/logic gap. Both codegen paths grow these four arms: the closed-expression path
    (x86_expr / code_size_expr) AND the program path with params/calls (x86_node / code_size_node).
    After the two operands are lowered (left then right pushed), each op pops rcx=right, rax=left.
    div: cqo (48 99) ; idiv rcx (48 f7 f9) ; push rax (50) -> quotient (8 bytes incl. the 59 58 pops).
    mod: cqo ; idiv rcx ; mov rax, rdx (48 89 d0) ; push rax -> remainder (11 bytes). Division is
    SIGNED, x86 idiv truncates toward zero, matching the interpreter oracle (Rust i64 /, %):
    -7/2 = -3, -7%2 = -1. Division/modulo by ZERO is UNGUARDED — idiv on a 0 divisor raises #DE
    (SIGFPE), which matches eval_expr: the interpreter returns a runtime error on `a/0` / `a%0`
    (it does NOT guard to 0). So both backends fault on a zero divisor — same observable contract.
    and/or are branchless on the eval (operand != 0) semantics: test rax,rax ; setne al ; test
    rcx,rcx ; setne cl ; and al,cl (or `or al,cl` = 08 c8) ; movzx eax,al ; push rax (20 bytes each).
    code_size arms: div +8, mod +11, and +20, or +20 — counted byte-for-byte against the emit arms
    so the program path's call/if rel32 offsets stay exact. VERBOSE-ONLY: four new op arms in each of
    x86_expr / code_size_expr / x86_node / code_size_node; no src change. Verified end-to-end
    (streaming_x86_divmod_logic, mmap+exec == eval_expr): 10/3->3, 10%3->1, 100/7->14, 100%7->2,
    -7/2->-3, -7%2->-1, 5 and 0->0, 5 and 3->1, 0 or 0->0, 0 or 7->1, (2<3) and (4<5)->1,
    1 and (if 1<2 then 1 else 0)->1; plus the program path (div in a proc, `and`/`%` across a call).

62. Records-arc brick R1: ACCEPT top-level `concept` declarations in the self-hosted
    parser. Before R1, parse_program (brick 12) walked top-level items recognizing only
    `rule` (span_is_rule) and STOPPED (RNil) on anything else — so a program containing a
    `concept` declaration silently DROPPED every rule after it. R1 teaches parse_program to
    SKIP concept blocks (so rules after a concept are still parsed), and adds a SEPARATE
    parse_concepts entry point that CAPTURES the concepts into a ConceptList. parse_program's
    return type stays RuleList (all call sites untouched); only its loop gains a skip-concept
    branch. New concepts (inside the VExpr group): Concept (MkConcept of name span + FieldList),
    FieldList (FCons of name span + type code + rest | FNil), ConceptList (CCons | CNil), and
    ParsedConcept (MkPC of Concept + end index) for position threading. New rules: span_is_concept
    / span_is_fields (byte-recognize `concept`/`fields`, mirroring span_is_rule/span_is_logic),
    parse_field / parse_fields (a field line is `IDENT : TYPE`, type via type_code_of_span; FNil at
    the dedent/end of the fields block), parse_concept_decl / parse_concept_decl_pos (header is
    `concept NAME` then a `fields:` block, mirroring parse_rule_decl / parse_rule_decl_pos),
    parse_concepts (the new top-level walk: at each item, if `concept` -> parse + CCons + recurse
    from its end; if `rule` -> SKIP past it + recurse; else CNil), concept_list_len / find_concept,
    and the drivers count_concepts / concept_field_count. CRITICAL INVARIANT: a rule-only program
    never takes parse_program's is_concept branch, so its RuleList is byte-identical to before. R1
    is parser+AST ONLY — no type checker change, no emitter change, no new lattice (AstField stays
    type code 3, deferred to R2). Fields are parsed for their name span and scalar type code; a
    concept-named field type just gets whatever type_code_of_span returns today (0). Validated by
    three orderings (concept->rule, rule->concept, two-concepts+rule) and the full existing suite
    staying byte-identical on the rule-only path.

63. Records-arc brick R2: SKIP what the self-hosted parser does not yet model, so count_rules works
    on REAL Verbose source (its own kind). Three skip-to-unblock changes, no new AST nodes. (R2.a)
    The line-driver tokenizer (tokenize_indent) now treats a line whose content starts with `--`
    (a full-line comment) or `@` (an attribute line like @intention / @source / @verbose) as BLANK
    — the same column-stack-untouched path as an empty line — so comments and attributes emit NO
    tokens and never perturb the INDENT/DEDENT structure. Full-line only: the self-source has no
    trailing comments on code lines (grep-verified). (R2.b) parse_program (and the sister capture
    walk parse_concepts) recognize a top-level `concept_group` header (span_is_concept_group, the
    13-byte ident, mutually exclusive with span_is_concept's 7-byte check) and SKIP its whole
    indented block via skip_indented_block, then recurse — so the rules declared AFTER the group
    are still found (before R2 the walk RNil'd on the group, the reason count_rules was 0 on real
    source). (R2.c) parse_rule_decl / parse_rule_decl_pos no longer require `logic:` immediately
    after the header: seek_logic scans forward over the rule's pre-logic blocks (input: / output:,
    whatever is not `logic`), skipping each whole via skip_indented_block until the `logic` header;
    and parse_rule_decl_pos computes its `next` STRUCTURALLY (skip the logic block, then if the next
    sibling is `proofs:`, skip that block too) so the program walk lands on the following top-level
    item independent of whether parse_stmts understood the (possibly rich) body. New concept
    SkipBlockState (cell + indent depth + seen flag). New rules: span_is_concept_group, span_is_proofs,
    skip_indented_block (depth-counted INDENT/DEDENT block skip), seek_logic. The heavy walks are
    gated behind the relevant span check (`if is_rule == 1 then ... else ...`, native lazy-if) so
    eager evaluation on a non-rule/non-group item stays cheap. Toy single-line grammars (logic: is
    the first header, no proofs) keep byte-identical behavior: seek_logic returns immediately and the
    structural `next` resolves to the same next-rule cell the old pb_next did after skip_seps_dedent.
    THE MILESTONE: count_rules on real self-source went 0 -> the actual `rule ` count.

64. Records-arc brick R3: PARSE the rule-body forms the self-source actually uses that R2 only
    SKIPPED — `::` variant construction and block-form `match` — into real AST instead of AstErr.
    PARSER-ONLY (downstream eval / type / checker / codegen get STUB arms; real handling is R6/R7).
    Two new Ast variants: AstVariant (a `Concept::Variant { field: expr, ... }` construction,
    concept-name span + variant-name span + a VFieldList of named initializers; the braceless form
    `Token::Eof` carries VFNil) and AstMatch (a `match scrut: Variant(binders) => body ...` with the
    scrutinee sub-expression and an ArmList). Three new cons-list group concepts mirror ArgList:
    VFieldList (VFCons/VFNil), ArmList (ArmCons/ArmNil), BinderList (BindCons/BindNil), plus three
    Parsed-threading results (ParsedVFields/MkVF, ParsedArms/MkAL, ParsedBinders/MkBL). `match` is
    lexed as a 5-byte keyword (kw5 code 11, kind 211) — the parse layer is source-free (ParseState
    carries only the token cell, no source bytes), so match is recognized by token kind exactly as
    `if` / `then` / `else` / `let` / `true` / `false` are, NOT by a span check. New parser rules:
    variant construction in parse_primary (an IDENT followed by `::` op 3 parses IDENT :: IDENT then
    an OPTIONAL `{ ... }`) via parse_vfields / vfields_cons / vfields_prepend / variant_build; and
    block-form match via parse_match / parse_arms / arm_join / parse_binders / binders_scan /
    binders_prepend (parse_arms reuses R2's INDENT/DEDENT separator skipping — skip_seps over Newline
    /Indent, stopping at Dedent/Eof — so both the indented self-source form and a flat single-line
    arm sequence parse). Adding the two Ast variants makes every `match` on an Ast value non-exhaustive,
    so all Ast-matching rules (eval_ast, eval_ast_env, shape_ast, type_of_env, the count_/span_
    analyses, print_expr, lower_expr/_src, x86_expr/_node, code_size_expr/_node) gain stub arms.
    shape_ast gives AstMatch (band 100000000) and AstVariant (band 1000000000) dedicated bands above
    AstStr's 10000000, with helpers shape_arms / shape_vfields recursing into arm bodies and field
    values — so a parsed match/variant body has a hand-derivable fingerprint distinct from the AstErr
    fingerprint (0). THE OBSERVABLE: the brick-5 `shape` driver on a body using both forms returns the
    predicted AstMatch + AstVariant fingerprint, proving the bodies now parse into real AST.

R6c — the interpreter evaluates match/variant (runtime Value model).
The evaluator was number-valued (eval_ast_env : number, and the whole call
machinery: venv_lookup / build_env / bind_params / eval_call). To evaluate a
match/variant program it must return a value that is a number OR a variant
(a tag + a payload); a number cannot hold a variant. So the eval subsystem
becomes Value-valued. Value = VNum(n) | VData(tag, payload); ValueList is the
payload cons-list; VEnv is the interpreter's runtime environment (name span ->
Value), kept separate from the R6b type checker's Env (which stores number type
codes). A variant's identity tag is self-computed from the parsed ConceptList of
the interpreted source: concept_index * 256 + variant_index (no global table).
A match recovers concept_index = tag / 256 from the scrutinee's tag, resolves
each arm's variant name to a tag, dispatches to the first equal arm, and binds
the arm's binders positionally to the scrutinee's payload. eval_ast becomes a
thin wrapper over eval_ast_env (unwrapping via vnum_of). Strings stay VNum 0
(deferred). eval_main threads the ConceptList so a program with a concept_group
and match/variant rules evaluates end to end (recursive list-sum -> the total).
